The paper deals with the combinatorial problem of generating a large number of sequences from a small initial string by tandem duplications of bounded length. This problem is related to the study of repeated sequences in the human genome, which is a topic of interest in computational biology. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics), which covers topics such as combinatorics, graph theory, and algorithms. 

The paper also involves the analysis of the capacity and expressiveness of tandem duplication systems, which can be seen as a form of language theory. This suggests that cs.GT (Computer Science and Game Theory) and cs.CC (Computational Complexity) are also likely sub-categories. 

Furthermore, the paper uses mathematical tools such as probability theory and information theory, which are relevant to cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.LG (Machine Learning). Therefore, these sub-categories are also possible.
